  'louisiana': { name: 'Louisiana', abbr: 'LA', icon: '\u{1f336}\ufe0f', topics: ['Civil Law', 'Property Rights', 'Business Law', 'Family Law'], content: 'Louisiana is unique among US states because it follows a civil law system based on French and Spanish legal traditions. The state has specific requirements for property rights, business formation, and family law matters.\n\n## Key Legal Areas in Louisiana\n\n### Civil Law System\nLouisiana follows a civil law system rather than common law, which means court decisions are not binding precedent. The state\'s laws are codified in the Louisiana Civil Code.\n\n### Property Rights\nLouisiana has unique property rights protections, including community property laws and specific requirements for property transfers.\n\n### Business Law\nLouisiana offers various business entity types and has specific filing requirements with the Secretary of State.\n\n### Family Law\Louisiana has specific family law provisions including community property rules and child custody guidelines.', keyLaws: ['Louisiana Civil Code', 'Louisiana Revised Statutes Title 9 (Corporations)', 'Louisiana Revised Statutes Title 9:354 (Civil Code)', 'Louisiana Code of Civil Procedure'], legalNotes: ['Civil law system unique in US', 'Community property state', 'Specific property transfer requirements', 'Business filing requirements'] },
